column3: The client SHOULD continue with its request. This interim response is used to inform the client that the initial part of the request has been received and has not yet been rejected by the server. The client SHOULD continue by sending the remainder of the request or
column4: if the request has already been completed
column5: ignore this response. The server MUST send a final response after the request has been completed. See section 8.2.3 for detailed discussion of the use and handling of this status code.

column3: The server understands and is willing to comply with the client's request
column4: via the Upgrade message header field (section 14.42)
column5: for a change in the application protocol being used on this connection. The server will switch protocols to those defined by the response's Upgrade header field immediately after the empty line which terminates the 101 response.

column3: The request has succeeded. The information returned with the response is dependent on the method used in the request
column4: for example:

column3: The request has been fulfilled and resulted in a new resource being created. The newly created resource can be referenced by the URI(s) returned in the entity of the response
column4: with the most specific URI for the resource given by a Location header field. The response SHOULD include an entity containing a list of resource characteristics and location(s) from which the user or user agent can choose the one most appropriate. The entity format is specified by the media type given in the Content-Type header field. The origin server MUST create the resource before returning the 201 status code. If the action cannot be carried out immediately
column5: the server SHOULD respond with 202 (Accepted) response instead.

column3: response MAY contain an ETag response header field indicating the current value of the entity tag for the requested variant just created
column4: see section 14.19.

column3: The request has been accepted for processing
column4: but the processing has not been completed. The request might or might not eventually be acted upon
column5: as it might be disallowed when processing actually takes place. There is no facility for re-sending a status code from an asynchronous operation such as this.

column3: The returned metainformation in the entity-header is not the definitive set as available from the origin server
column4: but is gathered from a local or a third-party copy. The set presented MAY be a subset or superset of the original version. For example
column5: including local annotation information about the resource might result in a superset of the metainformation known by the origin server. Use of this response code is not required and is only appropriate when the response would otherwise be 200 (OK).

column3: The server has fulfilled the request but does not need to return an entity-body
column4: and might want to return updated metainformation. The response MAY include new or updated metainformation in the form of entity-headers
column5: which if present SHOULD be associated with the requested variant.

column3: The server has fulfilled the request and the user agent SHOULD reset the document view which caused the request to be sent. This response is primarily intended to allow input for actions to take place via user input
column4: followed by a clearing of the form in which the input is given so that the user can easily initiate another input action. The response MUST NOT include an entity.

column3: The server has fulfilled the partial GET request for the resource. The request MUST have included a Range header field (section 14.35) indicating the desired range
column4: and MAY have included an If-Range header field (section 14.27) to make the request conditional.

column3: The requested resource corresponds to any one of a set of representations
column4: each with its own specific location
column5: and agent- driven negotiation information (section 12) is being provided so that the user (or user agent) can select a preferred representation and redirect its request to that location.

column3: The requested resource has been assigned a new permanent URI and any future references to this resource SHOULD use one of the returned URIs. Clients with link editing capabilities ought to automatically re-link references to the Request-URI to one or more of the new references returned by the server
column4: where possible. This response is cacheable unless indicated otherwise.

column3: The requested resource resides temporarily under a different URI. Since the redirection might be altered on occasion
column4: the client SHOULD continue to use the Request-URI for future requests. This response is only cacheable if indicated by a Cache-Control or Expires header field.

column3: The response to the request can be found under a different URI and SHOULD be retrieved using a GET method on that resource. This method exists primarily to allow the output of a POST-activated script to redirect the user agent to a selected resource. The new URI is not a substitute reference for the originally requested resource. The 303 response MUST NOT be cached
column4: but the response to the second (redirected) request might be cacheable.

column3: Not modified the client has performed a conditional GET request and access is allowed
column4: but the document has not been modified
column5: the server SHOULD respond with this status code. The 304 response MUST NOT contain a message-body
column6: and thus is always terminated by the first empty line after the header fields.

column3: The requested resource MUST be accessed through the proxy given by the Location field. The Location field gives the URI of the proxy. The recipient is expected to repeat this single request via the proxy. 305 responses MUST only be generated by origin servers.
The 306 status code was used in a previous version of the specification
column4: is no longer used

column3: The requested resource resides temporarily under a different URI. Since the redirection MAY be altered on occasion
column4: the client SHOULD continue to use the Request-URI for future requests. This response is only cacheable if indicated by a Cache-Control or Expires header field.

column3: The request could not be understood by the server due to malformed syntax. The client SHOULD NOT repeat the request without modifications.

The request requires user authentication. The response MUST include a WWW-Authenticate header field (section 14.47) containing a challenge applicable to the requested resource. The client MAY repeat the request with a suitable Authorization header field (section 14.8). If the request already included Authorization credentials
column4: then the 401 response indicates that authorization has been refused for those credentials. If the 401 response contains the same challenge as the prior response
column5: and the user agent has already attempted authentication at least once
column6: then the user SHOULD be presented the entity that was given in the response
column7: since that entity might include relevant diagnostic information. HTTP access authentication is explained in "HTTP Authentication: Basic and Digest Access Authentication" [43].

column3: This code is reserved for future use.
The server understood the request
column4: but is refusing to fulfill it. Authorization will not help and the request SHOULD NOT be repeated. If the request method was not HEAD and the server wishes to make public why the request has not been fulfilled
column5: it SHOULD describe the reason for the refusal in the entity. If the server does not wish to make this information available to the client
column6: the status code 404 (Not Found) can be used instead.

column3: The server has not found anything matching the Request-URI. No indication is given of whether the condition is temporary or permanent. The 410 (Gone) status code SHOULD be used if the server knows
column4: through some internally configurable mechanism
column5: that an old resource is permanently unavailable and has no forwarding address. This status code is commonly used when the server does not wish to reveal exactly why the request has been refused
column6: or when no other response is applicable.

column3: The method specified in the Request-Line is not allowed for the resource identified by the Request-URI. The response MUST include an Allow header containing a list of valid methods for the requested resource.
The resource identified by the request is only capable of generating response entities which have content characteristics not acceptable according to the accept headers sent in the request.
This code is similar to 401 (Unauthorized)
column4: but indicates that the client must first authenticate itself with the proxy. The proxy MUST return a Proxy-Authenticate header field (section 14.33) containing a challenge applicable to the proxy for the requested resource. The client MAY repeat the request with a suitable Proxy-Authorization header field (section 14.34). HTTP access authentication is explained in "HTTP Authentication: Basic and Digest Access Authentication" [43].

column3: The client did not produce a request within the time that the server was prepared to wait. The client MAY repeat the request without modifications at any later time.
The server encountered an unexpected condition which prevented it from fulfilling the request.

The server does not support the functionality required to fulfill the request. This is the appropriate response when the server does not recognize the request method and is not capable of supporting it for any resource.
The server
column4: while acting as a gateway or proxy
column5: received an invalid response from the upstream server it accessed in attempting to fulfill the request.

column3: The server is currently unable to handle the request due to a temporary overloading or maintenance of the server. The implication is that this is a temporary condition which will be alleviated after some delay. If known
column4: the length of the delay MAY be indicated in a Retry-After header. If no Retry-After is given
column5: the client SHOULD handle the response as it would for a 500 response.

column3: The server
column4: while acting as a gateway or proxy
column5: did not receive a timely response from the upstream server specified by the URI (e.g. HTTP
column7: LDAP) or some other auxiliary server (e.g. DNS) it needed to access in attempting to complete the request.

column3: The server does not support
column4: or refuses to support
column5: the HTTP protocol version that was used in the request message. The server is indicating that it is unable or unwilling to complete the request using the same major version as the client
column7: other than with this error message. The response SHOULD contain an entity describing why that version is not supported and what other protocols are supported by that server.
